==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*mēnan-'', from Indo-European ''*mēnōt-'', a suffixed form of an ultimate root ''*me-'' ‘measure’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''mōna'', Old Saxon ''māno'' (Dutch [[maan]]), Old High German ''māno'' (German [[Mond]]), Old Norse ''máni'' (Swedish [[måne]]), Gothic [[𐌼𐌴𐌽𐌰]].  The IE root was also the source of Greek [[μήν]] ‘month’, Latin [[mensis]], Old Irish ''mī'', Old Slavic ''měsęc’'' (Russian [[месяц]] ‘moon, month’).

